[1] Mexico (Jalisco)
Date: Wed 20 May 2009
Source: El Occidental [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.oem.com.mx/eloccidental/>


Together with Oaxaca [state], Jalisco [state] is now in 10th place
regarding the number of dengue cases [in Mexico]. The Secretariat of Health
yesterday [19 May 2009] confirmed 2 new patients from Puerto Vallarta and
Tonala, which raises the number to 126. Of these, 10 are DHF. This number
is greater than that of the same period in 2008, when 83 [dengue cases]
were recorded, acknowledged an official of the Department of Vectors and
Zoonoses, Fermina Espinosa Alcantar. Puerto Vallarta (40 cases) and
Casimiro Castillo (with 37) are the municipalities most affected. In
Guadalajara, there have been only 2 individuals ill with dengue.

A possible explanation for the increase in recorded cases is that the
states that border Jalisco, such as Colima and Michoacan, are in 1st place
in the country for [numbers of] dengue cases. "Dengue is a disease which
has a lot to do with population movements; we have had imported cases [in
individuals] who reside in the state of Jalisco, but who have vacationed in
places of high dengue incidence and return infected [with dengue virus],"
she explained.

Nationally, the state most infested by the vector that transmits the
disease [virus], the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, is Colima, with 1014
[dengue] cases. Michoacan has 624 cases, Guerrero 548, Veracruz 538,
Sinaloa 283, Morelos 199, and Nayarit 170.

[byline: Alfredo Ibarra Rivas]

--
