[3] Trinidad & Tobago
Date: Wed 20 May 2009
Source: Trinidad & Tobago's Newsday [edited]
<http://www.newsday.co.tt/news/0,100472.html>


At the St Ann's Psychiatric Hospital [Port-of-Spain Trinidad], 3 staff
members have contracted the mosquitoborne [virus] disease, dengue fever.
According to hospital sources, the outbreak occurred in the chronic wards
located on the hillside section of the compound. Newsday was told that the
source of the mosquito problem could be open toilet tanks in the washrooms
of some wards, which serve as breeding sites for mosquitoes. The tanks do
not have covers.

Another source linked the mosquito problem to a river flowing through the
grounds of the hospital. Newsday has learnt that some staff have complained
of the mosquito problem and spraying was carried out. Officials of the
North-West Regional Health Authority could not be reached for comment
yesterday [19 May 2009].

--
communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The sources of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes that transmit dengue virus
are water catchments in and immediately around the buildings, not the
river. The river may contribute to breeding of pest mosquitoes that are not
dengue virus vectors.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Trinidad & Tobago can be
accessed at <http://healthmap.org/r/00d1>. - Mod.TY]

