[5] Argentina (Chaco)
Date: Fri 22 May 2009
Source: El Libertario.com [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY. edited]
<http://www.ellibertario.com/2009/05/22/urbani-dice-que-se-minimizo-el-brote-epidemico-de-dengue/>


"The [dengue] epidemic in [neighboring] Bolivia," stated provincial
[health] minister Victor Urbani, "has been devastating, in that up to the
latest notifications which have been offered, 70 000 cases have been
recorded; and with due respect I must say that Bolivia is not a country
with adequate notification, so we must suppose that there are more cases
[than that].

"But beyond the number [of cases] that there have been, it is impossible to
avoid the arrival of dengue [virus] in our country [Argentina]. There are
no sanitary barriers, and it would be useless to [attempt to] control
movement or impede people from coming in," he stated.

Although assuredly Chaco has recorded about 13 000 [dengue] cases, he
stated that in Jujuy there have been fewer cases than in other provinces
such as Salta, Tucuman, and Catamarca. Minister Urbani reflected that in
the Jujuy area, there have been no DHF cases, attributed to the good
results of the work that has been done, which minimized the epidemic.

--
communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 20 May 2009 edition of Infobae.com (in Spanish)
(<http://www.infobae.com/contenidos/449500-0-0-Ocaña-asegura-que-el-brote-dengue-está-controlado>)
quotes Argentinean health minister Graciela Ocana saying that the dengue
outbreak has been controlled, and that there have been 25 157 recorded
dengue cases with 5 deaths. Some 92 per cent of the cases have been in the
provinces of Chaco (46 per cent), Catamarca (36 per cent), and Salta (10
per cent). The report adds that the Pan American Health Organization
indicated that the factors contributing to the resurgence of dengue in
Argentina are climatic changes and infrastructural deficiencies (water,
sanitation, trash collection) in cities with accelerating increases of
human populations.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing both northern Argentina and
Bolivia can be accessed at <http://healthmap.org/r/00d2>. - Mod.TY]

